00:00:00.580 --> 00:00:05.980
Let's say I have a subspace v
that is equal to all of the

00:00:05.980 --> 00:00:15.325
vectors-- let me write it this
way-- all of the x1, x2, x3's,

00:00:15.325 --> 00:00:24.980
so all the vectors like this
that satisfy x1 plus x2 plus

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:28.050
x3 is equal to 0.

00:00:28.050 --> 00:00:31.030
So if you think about it, this
is just a plane in R3, so this

00:00:31.030 --> 00:00:33.180
subspace is a plane in R3.

00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:37.810
And I'm interested in finding
the transformation matrix for

00:00:37.810 --> 00:00:44.350
the projection of any vector
x in R3 onto v.

00:00:44.350 --> 00:00:45.840
So how could we do that?

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:47.780
So we could do it like we
did in the last video.

00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:52.280
We could find the basis for
this subspace right there.

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:54.580
And that's not too hard to do.

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:59.290
We could say x1, if we assume
that, let's say, that x2 and

00:00:59.290 --> 00:01:02.080
x3 are kind of free variables,
then we could say that x1 is

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:07.550
equal to minus x2, minus x3.

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:10.940
And then let's just, just so we
can write it in, kind of,

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:15.130
our parametric form, or if we
can write our solution set as

00:01:15.130 --> 00:01:19.650
the combination of basis
vectors, we can say x2 is

00:01:19.650 --> 00:01:21.520
equal to, let's say
it's equal to some

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:23.930
arbitrary constant, C2.

00:01:23.930 --> 00:01:26.360
And let's say that x3
is equal to some

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:28.900
arbitrary constant, C3.

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:35.860
Then we can say that v, we can
rewrite v, we could say that v

00:01:35.860 --> 00:01:41.220
is-- I'll do it here-- v is
equal to the set of all x1's,

00:01:41.220 --> 00:01:51.590
x2's, and x3's that are equal
to C2 times-- so x1 is equal

00:01:51.590 --> 00:01:56.320
to minus-- let me rewrite
this with a C2--

00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:58.230
this is equal to C2.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:00.190
This is equal to C3.

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:05.050
So x1 is equal to minus
C2, minus C3.

00:02:05.050 --> 00:02:12.470
So x1 is equal to minus 1 times
C2, plus C3 times what?

00:02:12.470 --> 00:02:16.560
Plus C3 times minus 1.

00:02:16.560 --> 00:02:19.550
And then what is x2 equal to?

00:02:19.550 --> 00:02:20.470
x2 is just equal to C2.

00:02:20.470 --> 00:02:24.420
So it's 1 times C2,
plus 0, times C3.

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:28.450
x3 is just equal to C3,
so it's 0 times C2,

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:30.700
plus 1, times C3.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:34.410
And so this is another way
of defining our subspace.

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:39.810
All of the vectors that satisfy
this is equal to this

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:40.590
definition here.

00:02:40.590 --> 00:02:43.660
It's all the vectors whose
components satisfy, or that

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:47.450
lie in this plane, whose entries
lie in that plane.

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:50.420
And that's for any real
numbers right there.

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:55.590
Or another way of writing this,
